[8] New Jersey (Ocean County, Lakewood) ex Israel
Date: Thu 29 Nov 2018
Source: WPG Talk Radio [abridged, edited]
http://wpgtalkradio.com/lakewood-measles-cases-up-to-18/


The number of measles cases related to Lakewood has climbed to 18, with another 16 possible occurrences under investigation, according to an update from the Ocean County Health Department. According to the New Jersey Department of Health, the 3 newest cases developed when a person who had already been confirmed with measles in Lakewood visited family in Passaic while infectious. The 3 newest cases are from the same household.

The cases all stem from a 27-year-old Lakewood man who had traveled to Israel and was confirmed to have the measles at the end of October [2018]. The literal rash of Lakewood cases is one of several outbreaks in the New York area, including Brooklyn and Rockland County. The New York City Health Department reported 29 confirmed cases in Brooklyn since October [2018], while 80 cases were confirmed in Rockland County by its county health department.

[Byline: Dan Alexander]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The Ocean County Health Department continues to support and highly encourage the exclusion of nonvaccinated children from schools, preschools and daycare centers in the outbreak area. These entities have the authority to make that decision when an outbreak has been declared by the New Jersey Department of Health. The age range so far for the current outbreak is 6 months to 27 years.

Meanwhile, Central Hatzolah (covering all 5 boroughs of New York City) sent a letter to all their members informing them that they are required to show proof that they have been vaccinated. The letter in part reads:

"In light of the recent measles outbreak in several areas of New York City, the Executive Board, in consultation with the Department of Health and several infectious disease specialists, has made a determination regarding immunization requirements for all Hatzalah members.

"In order to protect our members, their families, and the community that we serve, every member will be required to provide proof of immunity for the following diseases: measles, mumps, rubella, varicella, [and] hepatitis B."

(Excerpted from https://www.theyeshivaworld.com/news/general/1632506/wednesday-measles-update-more-cases-in-lakewood.html). - Mod.LK]

